# Changes to GOV.UK Frontend v6.0.0

The main purposes of v6 are to update the colour palette to align with the GOV.UK Brand Guidelines, improve flexibility for template layout, and improve our Sass architecture for future improvements.

This release includes breaking changes to Sass support and removes a number of deprecated APIs, Sass variables and component options.

## Migrating from v5 to v6

Follow the guidance about [staying up to date with GOV.UK Frontend](https://frontend.design-system.service.gov.uk/staying-up-to-date/).

When making the decision to migrate, consider your service's requirements and your ability to update Sass tooling and templates. In particular, you must update to [Dart Sass v1.79.0 or newer](https://sass-lang.com/dart-sass/) before upgrading to v6.

## Benefits of updating to v6

By updating to v6 you'll:

- stay aligned with the GOV.UK look and feel: we've updated GOV.UK Frontend to use the web colour palette from the GOV.UK Brand Guidelines
- access updates to the way the web colour palette is used in certain components
- get the latest accessibility improvements, based on ongoing testing and feedback from services across government
- benefit from a smaller CSS payload
- be able to heavily customise your Page template

## Main changes to v6

This release updates the GOV.UK brand colours and typography, removes deprecated Sass and component APIs, and refactors the Page template nunjucks blocks to allow more flexible placement of components on the page. Read the details about the changes to v6 in [the release notes](https://github.com/alphagov/govuk-frontend/releases/v6.0.0).

There are actions you must make to migrate to v6.0.0. These are items you need to update, check or remove.

You'll need to update some items, which include:

- update your Sass compiler to [Dart Sass v1.79.0 or newer](https://sass-lang.com/dart-sass/)
- update colour usage to the GOV.UK web palette and use the `govuk-colour` function instead of the `$govuk-colours` map
- update any uses of functional colour variables to use the new `govuk-functional-colour` Sass function
- replace `govuk-tint` and `govuk-shade` with the new palette tints and shades
- replace `govuk-tag--light-blue` and update `govuk-tag--turquoise` to `govuk-tag--teal` and `govuk-tag--pink` to `govuk-tag--magenta`

You'll need to check some items still work as expected, which include:

- your service’s custom colours for contrast and legibility with the new web palette
- any custom components that reference functional colours or CSS custom properties
- any custom header or footer content if you now include Service navigation or Phase banner components within the `<header>` element

You'll need to remove the following items:

- the `$govuk-colours` variable
- the `govuk-responsive-typography` Sass mixin and any calls to `govuk-font-size` or `govuk-font` with `$size: 14`
- `govuk-body-xs` and `govuk-!-font-size-14` classes
- references to the `$govuk-new-typography-scale`, `$govuk-show-breakpoints` and `$govuk-new-organisation-colours` feature flags
- the `$legacy` parameter for `govuk-colour`
- service name and navigation items in the GOV.UK header component (use the Service navigation component instead)
